<handout>
  <title>Practice Exam 1</title>

<section>
<title>Topics</title>

    <p workspace="1in">
      Sections 0.2, 0.3, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, 1.4, 1.6, 1.7 
    </p>

    <p>
      Be sure to try each question before looking at the solutions.
    </p>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-practiceexam1">
    <title>Questions</title> 

    <exercise xml:id="classifying-des-exam">
  <!-- <title>Classifying Differential Equations</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      For each of the following differential equations, classify it according to the following criteria:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>whether it is <em>ordinary</em> or <em>partial</em>,</li>
      <li>its <em>order</em>,</li>
      <li>whether it is <em>linear</em> or <em>nonlinear</em>,</li>
      <li>and, if applicable, whether it is <em>homogeneous</em> or <em>non‑homogeneous</em>.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Classify the differential equation:</p>

    <me>
      y'' + 5y' - 6y = \sin x.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Recall the key definitions:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        An <em>ordinary differential equation</em> (ODE) involves a function of a single variable and its ordinary derivatives.  
      </li>
      <li>
        The <em>order</em> is the highest derivative present.  
      </li>
      <li>
        A differential equation is <em>linear</em> if the dependent variable and all its derivatives appear to the first power and are not multiplied together.  
      </li>
      <li>
        A linear differential equation is <em>homogeneous</em> if the right-hand side is zero; otherwise it is <em>non-homogeneous</em>.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The equation is an <em>ordinary</em> differential equation of <em>second order</em>, it is <em>linear</em>, and it is <em>non-homogeneous</em>.
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We analyze the equation
    </p>
    <me>
      y'' + 5y' - 6y = \sin x.
    </me>
    <p>
      First, because the unknown function is <m>y(x)</m>, a function of a single variable, and all derivatives are ordinary derivatives with respect to <m>x</m>,this is an <em>ordinary differential equation</em>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The highest derivative appearing is <m>y''</m>, so the <em>order</em> of the equation is <m>2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each occurrence of <m>y</m>, <m>y'</m>, and <m>y''</m> appears to the first power, and none are multiplied together or appear inside nonlinear expressions such as trigonometric, exponential, or power functions.
Therefore the equation is <em>linear</em>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A linear differential equation is homogeneous only when the right-hand side is identically zero.  Here the right-hand side is <m>\sin x</m>, which is not zero; hence the equation is <em>non-homogeneous</em>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Putting everything together: the equation is an <em>ordinary, second-order, linear, non-homogeneous differential equation</em>.
    </p>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="integrals-as-solutions-example">
  <!-- <title>Integrals as Solutions</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      y'(x) = 3x^2 - 4x + 1.
    </me>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>Find the general solution using an integral expression.</li>
        <li>Determine the particular solution satisfying the initial condition 
          <m>y(1)=2</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Recall that if <m>y'(x)=f(x)</m>, then any solution must satisfy
    </p>
    <me>
      y(x) = \int f(x)\,dx + C.
    </me>
    <p>
      Integrate term‑by‑term.  
      After finding the general solution, substitute <m>x=1</m> and <m>y=2</m> 
      to determine <m>C</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The general solution is 
      <m>y(x)=x^3 - 2x^2 + x + C</m>.  
      The initial condition <m>y(1)=2</m> gives <m>C=2</m>,  
      so the particular solution is 
      <m>y(x)=x^3 - 2x^2 + x + 2</m>.
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We begin with the differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      y'(x) = 3x^2 - 4x + 1.
    </me>
    <p>
      By the fundamental theorem of calculus, a solution must satisfy
    </p>
    <me>
      y(x) = \int (3x^2 - 4x + 1)\,dx + C.
    </me>
    <p>
      Integrating term‑by‑term:
    </p>
    <me>
      \int 3x^2\,dx = x^3,\qquad 
      \int (-4x)\,dx = -2x^2,\qquad
      \int 1\,dx = x.
    </me>
    <p>
      Therefore the general solution is
    </p>
    <me>
      y(x) = x^3 - 2x^2 + x + C.
    </me>
    <p>
      To find the particular solution satisfying <m>y(1)=2</m>, substitute 
      <m>x=1</m> into the general solution:
    </p>
    <me>
      2 = 1^3 - 2\cdot 1^2 + 1 + C = 1 - 2 + 1 + C = 0 + C.
    </me>
    <p>
      Thus <m>C = 2</m>, and the particular solution is
    </p>
    <me>
      y(x) = x^3 - 2x^2 + x + 2.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="slope-field-exam-problem">
  <!-- <title>Slope Field Interpretation</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      y' = x - y.
    </me>
    <p>
      Sketch a small portion of the slope field in the region 
      <m>-1 \le x \le 2</m>, <m>-1 \le y \le 2</m> by hand.  
      Then answer the following questions:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Determine whether the solution curve through the point 
        <m>(0,1)</m> is initially increasing or decreasing.  
        Justify your answer using the slope field.
      </li>
      <li>
        Without solving the differential equation explicitly,  
        describe the qualitative long–term behavior of solutions.  
        Do they tend toward a particular line, diverge, or behave  
        in some other way?
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Remember that the slope field is built from small line segments 
      whose slope equals <m>y' = x - y</m> at each point <m>(x,y)</m>.  
      For part (a), compute <m>y'</m> at the given point to determine 
      whether the local slope is positive or negative.  
      For part (b), think about values of <m>x - y</m> along the line 
      <m>y = x-1</m> and whether slopes push trajectories toward or away 
      from that line.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      (a) The solution through <m>(0,1)</m> is initially 
      <em>decreasing</em> because <m>y' = 0 - 1 = -1</m>.  
      (b) Solutions tend toward the line <m>y = x-1</m>, which acts as a 
      stable equilibrium line for the differential equation.
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
  <p>
    We are given the differential equation
  </p>
  <me>
    y' = x - y.
  </me>

  <p>
    To understand the qualitative behavior of solutions, we begin by noting
    that the slope field at each point <m>(x,y)</m> is determined by the value
    of <m>x - y</m>.  In particular:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      When <m>x - y = 0</m>, the slope is horizontal.
    </li>
    <li>
      When <m>x - y &gt; 0</m>, solution curves locally increase.
    </li>
    <li>
      When <m>x - y &lt; 0</m>, solution curves locally decrease.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    (a) At the point <m>(0,1)</m> we compute
  </p>
  <me>
    y' = x - y = 0 - 1 = -1.
  </me>
  <p>
    Because the slope is negative, the solution curve passing through 
    <m>(0,1)</m> initially decreases as <m>x</m> increases.
  </p>

    <figure xml:id="slopefield-x-minus-y">
  <caption>Slope field for <m>y' = x - y</m> on <m>-1 \le x \le 2</m>, <m>-1 \le y \le 2</m> together with a solution curve through <m>(0,1)</m>.</caption>
  <image width="50%">
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
  % Ensure a stable bounding box
  \draw[white] (-1.25,-1.25) rectangle (2.25,2.25);

  % Axes
  \draw[->] (-1.1,0) -- (2.1,0) node[below right] {$x$};
  \draw[->] (0,-1.1) -- (0,2.1) node[above left] {$y$};

  
  % Tick marks and labels on x-axis at -1, 1, 2
  \foreach \xx/\lbl in {-1/{$-1$}, 1/{$1$}, 2/{$2$}}{
    \draw (\xx,0.06) -- (\xx,-0.06) node[below=1pt] {\lbl};
  }
  % Tick marks and labels on y-axis at -1, 1, 2
  \foreach \yy/\lbl in {-1/{$-1$}, 1/{$1$}, 2/{$2$}}{
    \draw (0.06,\yy) -- (-0.06,\yy) node[left=1pt] {\lbl};
  }

  % Window frame and light grid
  \draw[gray!40] (-1,-1) rectangle (2,2);
  \draw[help lines,gray!20] (-1,-1) grid[step=0.5] (2,2);

  
  % The line y = x (in red), clipped to window
  \begin{scope}
    \clip (-1,-1) rectangle (2,2);
    \draw[very thick,red,dashed] (0,-1) -- (2,1);
  \end{scope}
  \node[red,above right] at (0.5,-0.75) {$y=x$};

  % Slope field for y' = x - y
  % Segment half-length parameter (adjust for density/visibility)
  \def\L{0.22}

  
 % Particular solution through (0,1): y = x - 1 + 2 e^{-x}
  % Draw it bold, clipped to the window
  \begin{scope}
    \clip (-1,-1) rectangle (2,2);
    \draw[very thick,black,domain=-1:2,samples=400]
      plot (\x, { \x - 1 + 2*exp(-\x) });
  \end{scope}
  % Mark and label the initial point (0,1)
  \fill (0,1) circle (1.3pt);
  \node[above right] at (0,1) {$(0,1)$};


  % Sample points (step = 0.25) over the window
  \foreach \x in {-1,-0.75,-0.5,-0.25,0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1,1.25,1.5,1.75,2}{%
    \foreach \y in {-1,-0.75,-0.5,-0.25,0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1,1.25,1.5,1.75,2}{%
      % Slope m = x - y, draw a short segment centered at (x,y) with angle atan(m)
      \pgfmathsetmacro{\m}{\x - \y}
      \pgfmathsetmacro{\ang}{atan(\m)}
      \pgfmathsetmacro{\dx}{0.5*\L*cos(\ang)}
      \pgfmathsetmacro{\dy}{0.5*\L*sin(\ang)}
      \draw[blue!70] (\x-\dx,\y-\dy) -- (\x+\dx,\y+\dy);
    }%
  }%
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>

  <p>
    (b) To analyze long–term behavior, we solve the differential equation.
    Rewriting it in linear form,
  </p>
  <me>
    y' + y = x,
  </me>
  <p>
    the integrating factor is <m>e^x</m>, and multiplying both sides yields
  </p>
  <me>
    (e^x y)' = x e^x.
  </me>
  <p>
    Integrating,
  </p>
  <me>
    e^x y = x e^x - e^x + C,
  </me>
  <p>
    and dividing by <m>e^x</m> gives the general solution
  </p>
  <me>
    y(x) = x - 1 + C e^{-x}.
  </me>

  <p>
    As <m>x \to \infty</m>, the exponential term <m>C e^{-x}</m> decays to zero.
    Therefore every solution approaches the straight line
  </p>
  <me>
    y = x - 1,
  </me>
  <p>
    which serves as the asymptotic line that solutions follow for large <m>x</m>.
    In particular, this line is an attracting solution curve: trajectories above it
    are pushed downward, and trajectories below it are
    pushed upward.
  </p>

  <p>
    The qualitative picture is that
    <em>all solutions to <m>y' = x - y</m> approach the line <m>y = x - 1</m> 
    as <m>x</m> increases.</em>
  </p>
</solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="separable-equation-corrected">
  <!-- <title>Solving a Separable Differential Equation</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      \dfrac{dy}{dx} = x(y+1).
    </me>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>Separate variables and find the general solution.</li>
        <li>Find the particular solution satisfying the initial condition 
          <m>y(0) = 2</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      First rewrite the equation so that all <m>y</m>-terms are on one side 
      and all <m>x</m>-terms on the other:
    </p>
    <me>
      \dfrac{1}{y+1}\,dy = x\,dx.
    </me>
    <p>
      Then integrate both sides.  
      After integrating, exponentiate to solve for <m>y</m>, and finally use 
      the initial condition to determine the constant.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The general solution is
      <me>y = C e^{x^{2}/2} - 1.</me>
      The initial condition <m>y(0)=2</m> gives <m>C=3</m>, so the particular
      solution is
      <me>y = 3 e^{x^{2}/2} - 1.</me>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Starting with the differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      \dfrac{dy}{dx} = x(y+1),
    </me>
    <p>
      we separate variables by dividing both sides by <m>(y+1)</m> and 
      multiplying by <m>dx</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \dfrac{1}{y+1}\,dy = x\,dx.
    </me>

    <p>Integrate both sides:</p>
    <me>
      \int \dfrac{1}{y+1}\,dy = \int x\,dx.
    </me>

    <p>Compute the integrals:</p>
    <me>
      \ln|y+1| = \dfrac{x^{2}}{2} + C.
    </me>

    <p>
      Exponentiating,
    </p>
    <me>
      |y+1| = e^{\,x^{2}/2 + C}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Write <m>e^{C}</m> as a new positive constant <m>C_1</m>, giving
    </p>
    <me>
      y + 1 = C_1 e^{x^{2}/2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solving for <m>y</m> produces the general solution:
    </p>
    <me>
      y = C_1 e^{x^{2}/2} - 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Apply the initial condition <m>y(0)=2</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      2 = C_1 e^{0} - 1 = C_1 - 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Hence <m>C_1 = 3</m>, and the particular solution is
    </p>
    <me>
      y(x) = 3 e^{x^{2}/2} - 1.
    </me>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="integrating-factor-no-absorption">
  <!-- <title>Solving a First-Order Linear Differential Equation</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the linear differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      y' - 3y = 6e^{2x}.
    </me>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>Find the general solution using the integrating factor method.</li>
        <li>Find the particular solution satisfying the initial condition <m>y(0)=4</m>.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Rewrite the equation in the standard linear form
      <me>y' + p(x)y = q(x)</me>
      and identify <m>p(x)=-3</m>.  
      The integrating factor is
    </p>
    <me>
      \mu(x) = e^{\int -3\,dx} = e^{-3x}.
    </me>
    <p>
      Multiply both sides of the equation by this integrating factor.  
      The left-hand side becomes <m>(e^{-3x}y)'</m>.  
      Integrate both sides, then multiply by <m>e^{3x}</m> to solve for <m>y</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The general solution is
      <me>
        y(x) = -6e^{2x} + C e^{3x}.
      </me>
      Using <m>y(0)=4</m> gives <m>C=10</m>, so the particular solution is
      <me>
        y(x) = -6e^{2x} + 10 e^{3x}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We begin with the linear differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      y' - 3y = 6e^{2x}.
    </me>
    <p>
      In linear form <m>y' + p(x)y = q(x)</m>, we have <m>p(x)=-3</m> and <m>q(x)=6e^{2x}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The integrating factor is
    </p>
    <me>
      \mu(x) = e^{\int -3\,dx} = e^{-3x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Multiply the entire differential equation by <m>e^{-3x}</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      e^{-3x} y' - 3 e^{-3x} y = 6 e^{2x} e^{-3x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The left-hand side is the derivative of <m>e^{-3x}y</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      (e^{-3x}y)' = 6 e^{-x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Integrate both sides:
    </p>
    <me>
      e^{-3x} y = \int 6 e^{-x}\,dx = -6 e^{-x} + C.
    </me>

    <p>
      Multiply both sides by <m>e^{3x}</m> to solve for <m>y</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      y = -6 e^{-x} e^{3x} + C e^{3x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Simplifying the exponential:
    </p>
    <me>
      y(x) = -6 e^{2x} + C e^{3x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      To find the constant <m>C</m>, apply the initial condition <m>y(0)=4</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      4 = -6 e^{0} + C e^{0} = -6 + C.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus <m>C = 10</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore the particular solution is
    </p>
    <me>
      y(x) = -6 e^{2x} + 10 e^{3x}.
    </me>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="autonomous-phase-diagram-correct">
  <!-- <title>Phase Diagram for an Autonomous Equation</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the autonomous differential equation
    </p>
    <me>
      x' = (1 - x)(3 - x)^2.
    </me>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Find all equilibrium solutions.
        </li>

        <li>
          Construct a <em>phase diagram</em> for this differential 
          equation. 
        </li>

        <li>
          Classify each equilibrium as stable, unstable, or semi-stable based 
          on your phase diagram.
        </li>

        <li>
          Describe the long-term behavior of solutions with 
          <m>x(0)=0</m>, <m>x(0)=2</m>, and <m>x(0)=4</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

  </statement>


  <hint>
    <p>
      Compute the sign of 
      <m>f(x) = (1-x)(3-x)^2</m> 
      in each region:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>x &lt; 1</m></li>
      <li><m>1 &lt; x &lt; 3</m></li>
      <li><m>x &gt; 3</m></li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Note that <m>(3-x)^2 \ge 0</m> for all <m>x</m>, and equals zero only when 
      <m>x=3</m>.  
      So the <em>sign</em> of <m>f(x)</m> is entirely determined by <m>(1-x)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Stability comes from arrow directions:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Arrows pointing toward the equilibrium implies stable.</li>
      <li>Arrows pointing away implies unstable.</li>
      <li>Arrows pointing toward on one side and away on the other implies semi-stable.</li>
    </ul>
  </hint>


  <answer>
    <p>
      Equilibria: <m>x = 1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>.  
      The phase diagram has arrows up for <m>x&lt;1</m>, 
      arrows down for <m>1&lt;x&lt;3</m>, and arrows down for <m>x&gt;3</m>.  
      Thus <m>x=1</m> is <em>stable</em>, and <m>x=3</m> is <em>semi-stable</em>.  
      Long-term behavior:
      <ul>
        <li><m>x(0)=0</m>: solution increases toward <m>x=1</m> from below.</li>
        <li><m>x(0)=2</m>: solution decreases toward <m>x=1</m> from above.</li>
        <li><m>x(0)=4</m>: solution decreases toward <m>x=3</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </answer>


  <solution>
    <p>
      (a)  Equilibria occur where
    </p>
    <me>
      (1-x)(3-x)^2 = 0,
    </me>
    <p>
      giving <m>x = 1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b)  To determine the sign of 
      <m>f(x) = (1-x)(3-x)^2</m>, 
      note that the squared factor <m>(3-x)^2</m> is always nonnegative and 
      equals zero only at <m>x = 3</m>.  
      Therefore the sign of <m>f(x)</m> is the sign of <m>(1-x)</m>.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        If <m>x &lt; 1</m>, then <m>1-x &gt; 0</m>, so <m>x' &gt; 0</m>.  
        Arrow: <em>up</em>.
      </li>

      <li>
        If <m>1 &lt; x &lt; 3</m>, then <m>1-x &lt; 0</m>, so <m>x' &lt; 0</m>.  
        Arrow: <em>down</em>.
      </li>

      <li>
        If <m>x &gt; 3</m>, then <m>1-x &lt; 0</m>, so <m>x' &lt; 0</m>.  
        Arrow: <em>down</em>.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      (c)  Therefore the phase diagram is as in <xref ref="phasediagramPE1N5"/>. 
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="phasediagramPE1N5">
      <caption>Phase diagram for <m>x'=(1-x)(3-x)^2</m>.</caption>
    <image width="10%">
      <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]

  % Vertical axis
  \draw[thick] (0,-1) -- (0,4);

  % Equilibria x = 1 and x = 3
  \fill (0,1) circle (2pt);
  \node[right] at (0,1) {$x = 1$};

  \fill (0,3) circle (2pt);
  \node[right] at (0,3) {$x = 3$};

  % Arrows:
  % x &lt; 1
  \draw[->, thick] (0,0.3) -- (0,0.9);

  % 1 &lt; x &lt; 3
  \draw[->, thick] (0,1.7) -- (0,1.1);

  % x &gt; 3
  \draw[->, thick] (0,3.7) -- (0,3.1);

\end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

    <p>
      Stability analysis:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <m>x = 1</m>: arrows point <em>towards</em> <m>x=1</m> on both sides so the equilibrium is 
        <em>stable</em>.
      </li>

      <li>
        <m>x = 3</m>: arrow from below points <em>away</em> from <m>x=3</m>, but arrow 
        from above points <em>downward</em> towards <m>x=3</m>.  
        Thus <m>x=3</m> is <em>semi-stable</em> equilibrium.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      (d)  Long–term behavior:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        If <m>x(0)=0</m>, then the arrow is upward; the solution moves toward 
        the stable equilibrium <m>x = 1</m>.
      </li>

      <li>
        If <m>x(0)=2</m>, the arrow is downward; the solution decreases toward 
        the stable equilibrium <m>x=1</m>.
      </li>

      <li>
        If <m>x(0)=4</m>, the arrow is downward; the solution decreases toward 
        the equilibrium <m>x=3</m>.
      </li>
    </ul>

  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="eulers-method-exam">
  <!-- <title>Euler's Method</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the initial value problem
    </p>
    <me>
      y' = x + y,  \qquad y(0) = 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Use Euler’s method with step size <m>h = 0.1</m> to approximate the
      value of <m>y(0.3)</m>.  
      Show your intermediate computations for each Euler step.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Recall that Euler’s method updates the approximate solution by
    </p>
    <me>
      y_{n+1} = y_n + h \, f(x_n, y_n),
    </me>
    <p>
      where <m>f(x,y) = x + y</m>.  
      Starting at <m>(x_0,y_0) = (0,1)</m> and using <m>h=0.1</m>,
      compute successively:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>y_1</m> at <m>x_1 = 0.1</m>,</li>
      <li><m>y_2</m> at <m>x_2 = 0.2</m>,</li>
      <li><m>y_3</m> at <m>x_3 = 0.3</m>.</li>
    </ul>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      Using Euler’s method with <m>h=0.1</m>,
      <m>y(0.3)</m> is approximately
      <me>y_3 = 1.462.</me>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We apply Euler’s method with <m>f(x,y) = x + y</m> and
      <m>h=0.1</m>.  
      The starting point is
    </p>
    <me>
      x_0 = 0, \qquad y_0 = 1.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Step 1:</strong>  Compute <m>y_1</m> at <m>x_1 = 0.1</m>.</p>
    <me>
      f(x_0,y_0) = 0 + 1 = 1,
    </me>
    <me>
      y_1 = y_0 + h f(x_0,y_0)
          = 1 + 0.1(1)
          = 1.1.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Step 2:</strong>  Compute <m>y_2</m> at <m>x_2 = 0.2</m>.</p>
    <me>
      f(x_1,y_1) = 0.1 + 1.1 = 1.2,
    </me>
    <me>
      y_2 = y_1 + h f(x_1,y_1)
          = 1.1 + 0.1(1.2)
          = 1.22.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Step 3:</strong>  Compute <m>y_3</m> at <m>x_3 = 0.3</m>.</p>
    <me>
      f(x_2,y_2) = 0.2 + 1.22 = 1.42,
    </me>
    <me>
      y_3 = y_2 + h f(x_2,y_2)
          = 1.22 + 0.1(1.42)
          = 1.22 + 0.142
          = 1.462.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, the Euler approximation of <m>y(0.3)</m> with 
      <m>h=0.1</m> is
    </p>
    <me>
      y(0.3) \approx 1.462.
    </me>
  </solution>

</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>
